 Langland’s Piers Plowman: The Possibility of Learning -- t“L’aage plus fort ennaye”: Scienta mortis, Ars moriendi and Jean Gerson’s Advice to an Old Man -- tRepresentations of Aging and Disability in Early Sixteenth-Century French Farce -- tThe Good, the Bad, and the Elderly: The Representation of Old Age in Netherlandish Prints (ca. 1550-1650) -- tHoorndragers and Hennetasters: The Old Impotent Cuckold as “Other” in Sixteenth- and Seventeenth-Century Netherlandish Art -- tA Portrait of the Artist as an Old Man – with Emphasis on Titian -- tThe Sulzbach Jubilee: Old Age in Early Modern Europe and America -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tList of Illustrations0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter an extensive introduction that takes stock of the relevant research literature on Old Age in the Middle Ages and the early modern age, the contributors discuss the phenomenon of old age in many different fields of late antique, medieval, and early modern literature, history, and art history. Both Beowulf and the Hildebrandslied, both Wolfram von Eschenbach's Parzival and Titurel, both the figure of Merlin and the trans-European tradition of Perceval/Peredur/Parzival, then the figure of the vetula in a variety of medieval French, English, and Spanish texts, and of the Old Man in The Stricker's Daniel, both the treatment of old age in Langland's Piers the Plowman and in Jean Gerson's sermons are dealt with. Other aspects involve late-antique epistolary literature, early modern French farce in light of Disability Studies, the social role of old, impotent men in sixteenth- and seventeenth-century Netherlandish paintings, and the scientific discourse of old age and health since the 1500s. The discourse of Old Age proves to have been of central importance throughout the ages, so the critical examination of the issues involved sheds intriguing light on the cultural history from late antiquity to the seventeenth century.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEuropean literatureyRenaissance, 1450-1600xHistory and criticism. 0aLiterature, MedievalxHistory and criticism. 0aOld age in literature. 0aOld agezEuropexHistory. 4aAlter /i. d. Literatur. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern Age.  aLate Antiquity.  aLiterature, History, and Art History.  aMiddle Ages.  aOld Age Studies.1 aBerthelot, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBostock, Sophie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClassen, Albrecht, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCoudert, Allison P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarver, Valerie L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGordon, Sarah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJanssen, Anouk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJost, Jean Ε., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLazda-Cazers, Rasma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Jonathan R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMieszkowski, Gretchen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeacock, Martha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeters, Harry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPigg, Daniel F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRothauser, Britt C. L.